This paper proposes a deep neural network for non-iterative reconstruction of compressively sensed images. The paper focuses on image processing and computer vision applications, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of measurement matrices and the optimization of reconstruction algorithms, which suggests that it may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The use of deep neural networks for end-to-end learning suggests that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also discusses experiments on real data obtained from a block compressive imager, which suggests that it may belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of the proposed algorithm for object tracking, which suggests that it may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
